ź’Ů@bbe95a90b332fa25e8fb548425639984cdd00392def93c9a515bb99b1178dc53ÚÎTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Nushell 0.71
Content:




Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your commandline. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful commandline pipelines.
Today, we're releasing version 0.71 of Nu. This release includes new operators, better consistency, improved completions, and more.
’Ů@bb8e38fd910c2f1e4c69910709c59602f519c4f51fa3dfebaf8a6f9eb8481d9fÚgTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Where to get it
Content:
Nu 0.71 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.71.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
If you want all the built-in goodies, such as support for dataframes and SQLite databases, you can install it via 
``cargo install nu --features=extra``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of optional plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
’Ů@500a7cd461f595c55c25b405b375de4971b1c2bab181610a1adec5dd8d53513bÚôTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path:  operator (merelymyself)
Content:
``++``
In this release, you can now use the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6766] ``++``
 operator to append lists together
.
For example, you can combine two lists into a new lists made up of the both lists:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1, 2] ++ [3, 4]

```
Note: Currently, this operator cannot be used to join two tables. This functionality is still being worked on and will likely be present in the next version.
’Ů@63e9642c862deeb194e9b1c2578b5edacc67638be0bd1bdeca1824c1e960e95dÚTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Improved consistency across commands and types
Content:
Nushell continues improve quality of the language and shell with a set of consistency improvements in this release. These include:
More 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6951] iterating filter commands
 now support the 
``$in``
 variable consistently (webbedspace)
Lists 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6932] now support 
``upsert``
 (fdncred)
``merge``
 can now also 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6919] operate on records
 (webbedspace)
``str substring``
 can 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6867] take ranges
 (rgwood)
``from``
 and 
``to``
 now 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6856] show help info
 (rgwood)
’Ů@8414de6c428c0105116a00cf16146b2601c5adb29314f8d81d59898f054b8e88ÚĄTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Right prompts can now be on the last line (nibon7)
Content:
Previously the right prompt appeared only on the same line where the user input started. Now you can choose to 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6781] place the right prompt part on the last line of user input
.

This feature is not enabled by default, you can enable it using the 
``config nu``
 command to modify the config.nu file, just set 
``render_right_prompt_on_last_line``
 to true:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
let-env config {
  render_right_prompt_on_last_line : true
  ...
}

```
Default
Default right prompt
Right prompt at bottom
Right prompt on the last line
’Ů@b2ed51ed40d44723dbc3c57e7ec74f2282bf5b90267461bdd5552ee6a27d05f4ÚzTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path:  hook (perbothner)
Content:
``display_output``
You're now able to configure a new hook, 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6915] called 
``display_output``
, which will become the default way that you view data.
Using this, you can for example, use 
``table --expand``
 to always see fully expanded tables.
If your terminal supports it, you can this to render a more full-featured output. For example, DomTerm could be used by setting the 
``display_output``
 hook to: 
``to html --partial --no-color | domterm hcat``
, sending html to the terminal to be rendered when displaying values.
’Ů@5a62e2fb96e4f0fd8ff8411be39017dfd55ea20b2cafa08890f1e6dc6fc2f8b1ÚíTitle: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Updated PR Review Process
Content:
Recently, we have been fortunate to see a rise in submitted pull requests (PRs) and we are super grateful for this growing desire to improve Nushell.

Unfortunately, in some cases, a well-intended PR does not match the direction Nushell is going, forcing us to close it which leads to wasted time and effort.

To help focus PRs in the future, we kindly ask potential contributors to first reach out to us before making a substantial change to Nushell, especially if the change will affect user experience.

We updated our 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md] contributing guide
 as well as the PR template to reflect this policy.

To summarize:
If you want to make some change to Nushell that is more involved than simple bug-fixing, please go to 
[link: https://discordapp.com/invite/NtAbbGn] Discord
 or a 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/issues/new/choose] GitHub issue
 and chat with some core team members and/or other contributors about it.
After getting a green light from the core team, implement the feature, open a pull request (PR) and write a full description of the change.
If your PR includes any user-facing features (such as adding a flag to a command), clearly list them in the PR description.
Then, core team members and other regular contributors will review the PR and suggest changes.
When we all agree, the PR will be merged.
If your PR includes any user-facing features, make sure the changes are also reflected in 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell.github.io] the documentation
 after the PR is merged.
Congratulate yourself, you just improved Nushell! :-)
We hope the new policy will help us make the PR review process smoother.
’Ů@882aae2879122923b4f3f77c205be384614805c757eb624425e015fd7a6a9430Ú>Title: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Completion actions now more familiar (dandavison)
Content:
We've also recently improved how completions work in Nushell to feel closer to how other shells work. Specifically:
Completion goes "as far as possible". So, the entire word if there's a unique completion, or else up to the shared prefix of possible completions.
Removes the quick completion behavior whereby a word was completed automatically as soon as the input came to have a unique completion.
Tab now completes instead of selecting the next menu item (this can be configured)
’Ů@26c3fea5f1728d7428f3aafdd636bf960353d67a688b52263db80ec36e0e0ed8Ú$Title: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Breaking changes
Content:
New 
``--force (-f)``
 flag for the 
``mv``
 command. This change alters 
``mv``
 default behavior. By default overwriting existing files is now prevented (You can use 
``alias mv = mv -f``
 in you config to get the old defaults back). (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6904] #6904
)
The column name for the command name in 
``$nu.scope.commands``
 has been changed from 
``command``
 to 
``name``
. Thus, 
``$nu.scope.commands | where name =~ zip``
 would give you specific command info. (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/7007] #7007
)
The 
``str distance``
 command now directly returns an 
``Int``
 instead of a record 
``{"distance": <Int>}``
 (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6963] #6963
)
The argument order of 
``format filesize``
 was made consistent with other commands that accept a 
``CellPath``
 to specify fields that should be affected by it. Now the string specifying the format is the first positional argument and the cell path is specified in the following positional argument(s). (
[
#6879
]
https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6879)
The 
``--perf``
 flag for Nu was removed as part of an effort to simplify diagnostics logging 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/6834] #6834
’Ů@f41276d16d8922596c03ec34c808b2ced3caa05ea20d779df5864e758a13cbb0Ú?Title: title: Nushell 0.71
Path: Next Steps
Content:
We've drafted a version of the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell.github.io/pull/656] design philosophy for 0.80
, and would love to get your feedback. If you'd like to become part of the effort, please 
[link: https://discord.gg/NtAbbGn] join the discord
.
